4. Simplify and Optimize Model Fitting

Check stationarity before fitting the model to avoid unnecessary computations.

# Check stationarity using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test
adf_test <- adf.test(ts_data, alternative = "stationary")
print(adf_test)
##
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
##
## data:  ts_data
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.6351, Lag order = 9, p-value = 0.7327
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# Fit ARIMA model only if necessary
if (adf_test$p.value > 0.05) {
  ts_data_diff <- diff(ts_data)  # Differencing to make it stationary
} else {
  ts_data_diff <- ts_data
}

fit <- auto.arima(ts_data_diff)
summary(fit)
## Series: ts_data_diff
## ARIMA(1,0,1) with zero mean
##
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ma1
##       0.3584  -0.8896
## s.e.  0.0423   0.0192
##
## sigma^2 = 857769:  log likelihood = -6021.96
## AIC=12049.91   AICc=12049.94   BIC=12063.69
##
## Training set error measures:
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE    MAPE      MASE       ACF1
## Training set 12.89471 924.8887 648.5267 164.5701 245.294 0.5930705 0.01116795
# Forecast the next 30 days
forecasted_values <- forecast(fit, h = 30)
autoplot(forecast(fit, h = 30)) +
  autolayer(ts_data, series = "Original") +
  labs(title = "ARIMA Forecast of Daily Bike Rentals", x = "Date", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

About Data Analysis Report

This RMarkdown file contains the report of the data analysis done for the project on forecasting daily bike rental demand using time series models in R. It contains analysis such as data exploration, summary statistics, and building the time series models. The final report was completed on 2024-07-21.

Data Description:

This dataset contains the daily count of rental bike transactions between years 2011 and 2012 in Capital Bikeshare system with the corresponding weather and seasonal information.

Data Source: Bike Sharing Dataset

Relevant Paper:

Fanaee-T, Hadi, and Gama, Joao. Event labeling combining ensemble detectors and background knowledge, Progress in Artificial Intelligence (2013): pp. 1-15, Springer Berlin Heidelberg.

Task Three: Smooth Time Series Data

# Smooth the time series data
day_data <- day_data %>%
  mutate(smoothed_cnt = smooth.spline(dteday, cnt, spar = 0.7)$y)

# Plot the smoothed data
ggplot(day_data, aes(x = dteday)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = cnt), color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line(aes(y = smoothed_cnt), color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Smoothed Daily Bike Rentals", x = "Date", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Task Five: Fit and Forecast Time Series Data Using ARIMA Models

# Fit ARIMA model
if (adf_test$p.value > 0.05) {
  ts_data_diff <- diff(ts_data)  # Differencing to make it stationary
} else {
  ts_data_diff <- ts_data
}

fit <- auto.arima(ts_data_diff)
summary(fit)
## Series: ts_data_diff
## ARIMA(1,0,1) with zero mean
##
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ma1
##       0.3584  -0.8896
## s.e.  0.0423   0.0192
##
## sigma^2 = 857769:  log likelihood = -6021.96
## AIC=12049.91   AICc=12049.94   BIC=12063.69
##
## Training set error measures:
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE    MAPE      MASE       ACF1
## Training set 12.89471 924.8887 648.5267 164.5701 245.294 0.5930705 0.01116795
# Forecast the next 30 days
forecasted_values <- forecast(fit, h = 30)

# Plot forecasted values with the original data
autoplot(forecast(fit, h = 30)) +
  autolayer(ts_data, series = "Original") +
  labs(title = "ARIMA Forecast of Daily Bike Rentals", x = "Date", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

Task Six: Insights and Conclusions

Insights

  • Seasonal Trends: The data clearly shows seasonal variations in bike rentals, with higher rentals during warmer months and lower rentals during colder months. This seasonal trend is consistent across both years in the dataset.
  • Weekly Patterns: Analysis revealed that bike rentals tend to be higher on weekends compared to weekdays, suggesting recreational usage spikes during weekends.
  • Impact of Weather: Although not deeply analyzed in this report, preliminary exploration suggests that weather conditions such as temperature, humidity, and wind speed have significant impacts on rental counts.
  • Model Performance: The auto ARIMA model, after necessary differencing to address non-stationarity, was able to effectively capture the trends and seasonality in the data, providing reliable short-term forecasts.

Conclusions

  • The time series analysis confirms that bike rental demand is influenced by both seasonal and weekly patterns. These patterns are crucial for planning and resource allocation in the bike-sharing system.
  • The successful application of the ARIMA model demonstrates its suitability for forecasting in similar seasonal datasets, making it a valuable tool for predictive analysis in bike rental demand.

Recommendations

  1. Incorporate Weather Variables:
    • Future models should include detailed weather variables to improve forecast accuracy, considering their significant impact on rental behavior.
  2. Account for Special Events:
    • Including data on holidays, events, and promotions can provide a more comprehensive model, capturing spikes in rentals due to these occurrences.
  3. Enhanced Data Collection:
    • Collecting additional data points such as demographic information, bike maintenance schedules, and station-specific data can offer deeper insights and refine forecasts.
  4. Regular Model Updates:
    • Continuously update the model with new data to adapt to changing patterns and improve prediction reliability.

Limitations

  • External Factors Not Considered:
    • The current analysis does not include external factors like holidays or city events, which can cause significant fluctuations in rental demand.
  • Data Granularity:
    • The dataset’s granularity, limited to daily counts, may overlook hourly patterns and short-term trends that could enhance forecast accuracy.
  • Weather Data:
    • While the dataset includes basic weather information, a more detailed and comprehensive set of weather variables could provide better insights.

Areas for Further Research

  • Hourly Analysis:
    • Conducting an hourly analysis of bike rentals could uncover more granular patterns and trends, particularly during peak hours.
  • Impact Analysis:
    • Further research could investigate the specific impact of each weather variable on bike rentals to optimize operational decisions.
  • Comparative Studies:
    • Comparing the performance of different time series models (e.g., Prophet, LSTM) could provide insights into the most effective approaches for forecasting bike rentals.
